Actually, the focus shifted in the second movie.  That's when Zion learned about the planned attack.  Which you can't really knock points off because the movie shifted because, well, it had to.  But you can knock off points for actually creating the problem that led to the shift (having the machines attack Zion in the story).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And let's involve the Merovingian but give him absolutely no real purpose in the story either. I mean the part he played could have been eliminated entirely without any impact. He added nothing. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The Merovingian's role was one of those subtle, &quot;let's push the main character along&quot; type characters.  Think Liv Tyler's Arwen in LoTR.  Her role isn't necessary or required and it's small, but it was given a reason for being there.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And I really didn't buy that they'd leave a guy they suspected of killing lots of people completely unguarded and alone with the doctor. There's suspension of belief for a story, and then there's just stupid.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, he was unconscious at the time, but yeah I see the point.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And then there was the absolutely pointless death right at the end. I mean I'm all for offing people, but it had no purpose whatsoever. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Talking about Neo's death?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Overall though, I felt like there was no payoff at all. At least I can hold out hope for Kill Bill volume 2. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
